Impulse Train¶

120 Hz:

In [76]:
#importing libraries
import scipy.signal as signal
from IPython.display import Audio, display
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
arr=[]
for i in range(60):
  arr.append(int(i*133.33))
#Generating a triangular pulse for 60 samples in an array of 8000 samples, so when sampling rate is 16000 Hz, the signal frequency will be 120 Hz
#imp120 = signal.unit_impulse(8000, arr)
#plotting on the time axis, for sampling rate 16000, there will be 10000 samples in 0.625 seconds
t=np.linspace(0,0.5,8000)
imp120=np.zeros(8000)
for i in range (8000):
  if i in arr:
      imp120[i]=1
      imp120[i-3]=1/4
      imp120[i-2]=1/2
      imp120[i-1]=3/4
      imp120[i+3]=1/4
      imp120[i+2]=1/2
      imp120[i+1]=3/4

plt.plot(t, imp120)
#labelling graph
plt.xlabel('Time(s)')
plt.ylabel('Amplitude')
plt.title('Triangular pulse train full')
plt.show()
plt.plot(t[:1000], imp120[:1000])
plt.xlabel('Time(s)')
plt.ylabel('Amplitude')
plt.title('Triangular pulse train cropped')
plt.show()
plt.plot(t[50:150], imp120[50:150])
plt.xlabel('Time(s)')
plt.ylabel('Amplitude')
plt.title('Single Triangular pulse')
plt.show()

Vowel /u/¶

In [78]:
#importing libraries
import scipy
import math
from scipy import signal
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.io.wavfile import write

#assigning values
f1=300.0
f2=870.0
f3=2240.0
b1=100.0
fs=16000.0
ts=1.0/fs

#calculating coefficients of transfer function
r=pow(math.e,-1*math.pi*b1*ts)
theta1=2*math.pi*f1*ts
theta2=2*math.pi*f2*ts
theta3=2*math.pi*f3*ts
z=[0,0,0,0,0,0]
p=[r*pow(math.e,1j*theta1), r*pow(math.e,-1*1j*theta1), r*pow(math.e,1j*theta2),r*pow(math.e,-1*1j*theta2),r*pow(math.e,1j*theta3),r*pow(math.e,-1*1j*theta3) ]
a,b=scipy.signal.zpk2tf(z, p, 1)
print(a)
print(b)

[1. 0. 0. 0. 0. 0. 0.]
[  1.          -5.04534821  11.22737737 -14.20053893  10.79502409
  -4.6642491    0.88886517]

In [79]:
#transfer function as a discrete linear time invariant system
system = signal.dlti(a, b, dt=0.0000625)
#magnitude response vs frequency
freq, resp= signal.dlti.freqresp(system,n=200)
#scaling axes (Y axis in decibel and x axis using sampling frequency)
plt.plot(16000*freq/(2*math.pi),20*np.log10(np.abs(resp)))
#labelling graph
plt.xlabel('Frequency (Hz)')
plt.ylabel('Magnitude response (dB)')
plt.title('Filter Magnitude response vs Frequency')

out120=np.zeros_like(imp120)
for i in range(8000):
  if (i==0 or i==1 or i==2 or i==3 or i==4 or i==5):
    out120[i]=0
  else:
    out120[i]=(imp120[i]-b[1]*out120[i-1]-b[2]*out120[i-2]-b[3]*out120[i-3]-b[4]*out120[i-4]-b[5]*out120[i-5]-b[6]*out120[i-6])

    #plotting the output of the filter
t=np.linspace(0,0.5,8000)
plt.plot(t[:1000], out120[:1000])
plt.xlabel('Time(s)')
plt.ylabel('Amplitude')
plt.title('Output on passing 120Hz input (few pulses)')
plt.show()
plt.plot(t, out120)
plt.xlabel('Time(s)')
plt.ylabel('Amplitude')
plt.title('Output on passing 120Hz input (entire signal)')
plt.show()

Hamming window¶

5ms:

--120Hz

In [84]:
samples=int(0.005*16000)
win=out120[10*samples:11*samples]*np.hamming(samples)
dft=np.fft.fft(win,1024)
freq=np.fft.fftfreq(dft.shape[-1],0.0000625)

#scaling axes (Y axis in decibel and x axis using sampling frequency)
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = [12, 3.50]
plt.plot(freq,20*np.log10(np.abs(dft)))
#labelling graph
plt.xlabel('Frequency (Hz)')
plt.ylabel('Magnitude response (dB)')
plt.title('DFT Magnitude response vs Frequency- [HAMMING][5MS][120Hz]')
plt.xlim(0,8000)
plt.xticks(np.arange(0,8000,100),rotation='vertical')
plt.yticks(np.arange(0,100,10),rotation='vertical')
plt.grid("True")

Values and error¶

Error in F1,F2,F3 increases as you increase window size

Error in F0 decreases as you increase window size

Error in F1,F2,F3 is more in rectangular than Hamming

Error in F0 is more in Hamming than rectangular

Comments¶

Smaller the window length:

Smoother the plot

Wider the main lobe

Less visible harmonics

More clear formants

Pitch info lost

Thus on increasing window length we go from wide band to narrow band

Hamming window gives wider main lobe than rectangular window

Faster Decay from main lobe to side lobes for hamming than rect (side lobes much lower than main lobe in hamming)

Hamming window has clearer formants while rectangular window has clearer pitch info (peaks closely spaced in rectangular)

F0=>Count peak interval in large window spectrum (narrow band)

Formants which are multiples of F0 are visualized clearly

Error in F1,F2,F3 increases as you increase window size

Error in F0 decreases as you increase window size

Error in F1,F2,F3 is more in rectangular than Hamming

The options below are convenience aliases to configurable class-options,

    Continue notebook execution even if one of the cells throws an error and include the error message in the cell output (the default behaviour is to abort conversion). This flag is only relevant if '--execute' was specified, too.
    Equivalent to: [--ExecutePreprocessor.allow_errors=True]

    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.from_stdin=True]

    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.writer_class=StdoutWriter]

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to html

            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic', 'lab' and
            'classic'. You can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template lab mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
